View of the north-western side and western corner of structure DDL0180-004. The structure is a quadrangular tower with two doorways, one in the south-west and one in the north-west.

The walls are built using carved and roughly cut stones, as well as architectural elements coming from other buildings.

imagebefore2015description:
Source: Locke 1985, 167

The description and photo that Locke provides for the Jisvā̃ Bāhā/Devarāja Vihāra match this monument. However, he describes a different bāhāḥ as Nandaya Bū Bāhā/Devajyoti Vihāra (p. 169-171).

imagebefore2015caption: Lalabaiṭhaka, view from W; anonymous; ca 1830s
imagebefore2015description:
Bhaktapur Darbar Square before the 1934 earthquake

The photograph shows the eastern part of the Lalabaiṭhaka, the Golden Gate and the Fifty-Five Window Palace next to it. Both the three-tiered temple of Harishankar and the Eight-Corner Pavilion of Chyasilin Mandap were lost in the 1934 earthquake. Chyasilin Mandap was rebuilt with German aid in 1989.

Source: Pruscha 1975, vol. 1, p. 99

View of Kvaylāchi with the caitya at the centre and the courtyard surrounded by traditional Newar houses. A portion of the Phalcā is seen on the right. In the foreground is the pond reflecting the surrounding environment. It does not exist any longer.

Following the 1934 earthquake, the roof and bell tower are severly damaged.

Degutale Temple to the right collapsed completely.

imagebefore2015description:
This side of the pillar is very damaged, probably because of the collapse of the roof.

The base of the pillar contains a bas-relief carving of Sūrya.

imagebefore2015caption: Setibada Baiṭhaka, south-western corner pillar, view from west; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2015-04-10
imagebefore2015description: The base of the pillar is decorated with the carving of a dancing character.

imagebefore2015caption: Setibada Baiṭhaka, western entablature, view from east; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2015-04-10
imagebefore2015description:
The inner side of the entablature contains an inscriptions set to the left and to the right of a bas-relief image of a standing deity. Above the left section of the inscription is another carved image, probably of Gaṇeśa.

The lower and upper parts of the entablature show strickingly different states of erosion. This is a likely indicator of the collapse of the structure.

imagebefore2015caption: Setibada Baiṭhaka, south-western corner pillar, view from south; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2015-04-10
imagebefore2015description: The pillar is richly adorned by decorative carvings and, at the base, the representation of a deity, presumably Sūrya.

imagebefore2015description:
View of the southwestern corner pillar. The upper register contains an interesting representation of the kalaśa pot depicted in a rather geometrical manner, with only straight lines.

The lower register presents a central losange, or diamond or jewel motif (ratna), framed on each side by another diamond motif.

imagebefore2015caption: Ajayamerukoṭa Baiṭhak, view from north; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2015-04-11
imagebefore2015description: Stone slabs are missing at the centre of the platform. Note the massive stone beam supporting the dome.

imagebefore2015caption: Ajayamerukoṭa Baiṭhak, view from north; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2015-04-11
imagebefore2015description: The area surrounding the pavilion is often used for picnics. This activity generates an important pollution of the site.

imagebefore2015caption: Ajayamerukoṭa Baiṭhak, view from south-east; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2015-04-11
imagebefore2015description:
View of the western side's central pillar. On top, below the cruciform capital, are crving of the kalaśa motif. below are vertical friezes with foliages. 

The lower register is damaged.

imagebefore2015caption: Ajayamerukoṭa Baiṭhak, ceiling of the pavilion; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2015-04-11
imagebefore2015description: The keystone is finely carved with a tridimensional lotus flower motif.
